        <subsection>
            <title>Inputs have unique outputs</title>
            <p>An important property of functions is that any single input value can only have one output value.</p>
            <example>
              <p>For example, when you buy a car it usually comes with a sticker on the window that includes information about the fuel efficiency.  Cars are tested on a track under controlled conditions and most likely the manufacturer has all kinds of graphs and tables for the efficiency measures for various speeds of the car.</p>
              <p>Let <m>E</m> be the fuel efficiency, in miles per gallon, of a car traveling at <m>s</m> miles per hour. Using function notation we can write <me>E = f(s)</me></p>
              <figure xml:id="speed-vs-efficiency">
                    <caption>Fuel Economy versus Speed</caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[xmin=5,xmax=75,
                                                ymin=0,ymax=35,
                                                xlabel={Speed (mph)},
                                                ylabel={Fuel Economy (mpg)},
                                                xtick={10,20,...,70},
                                                minor xtick={-5,0,...,75},
                                                ytick={0,10,...,30},
                                                minor ytick={0,5,...,35},
                                                axis line style = {->},]
                                        \addplot+[smooth,->] coordinates {(5, 11) (10, 19) (15, 24) (20, 26.5) (25, 28) (30,29) (35, 29.5) (40, 30) (55, 30.5) (65,26.5) (70, 25) (75, 24)};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>
              <p>The input is the speed, <m>s</m>, and the output is the efficiency, <m>E</m> so we can write an ordered pair <m>(s, E)</m> or <m>(s, f(s))</m>.</p>
              <p>It should make sense that a car can only have one efficiency at any given speed since it cannot get <quantity><mag>10</mag><unit base="milepergallon" /></quantity> and <quantity><mag>20</mag><unit base="milepergallon" /></quantity> at the same time.</p>
              <p>However, it is possible there are multiple inputs that give you the same output.  From the graph we see that a fuel efficiency of <quantity><mag>25</mag><unit base="milepergallon" /></quantity> can be attained by traveling at a speed of about <quantity><mag>20</mag><unit base="mileperhour"/></quantity> and also at about <quantity><mag>70</mag><unit base="mileperhour"/></quantity>.</p></example>

