        <subsection>
            <title>Describing functions with intervals</title>
            <p>A function may have many different characteristics:</p>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li><p>Output values may increase or decrease.</p></li>
                <li><p>The graph may curve up or curve down.</p></li>
                <li><p>The outputs may be positive or negative.</p></li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            <p>When describing these characteristics for a function, we typically refer to an <term>interval</term><index><main>interval</main></index> (connected section) of the input axis, or to a particular value of the input where something interesting occurs.</p>

            <p>We can use <term>inequality</term><index><main>inequality</main></index> symbols to describe an interval where a function has a particular property, like increasing for <m>5\lt s\lt55</m>.  This means the function values are getting bigger as the inputs change from <m>5</m> to <m>55</m>.</p>
            <todo>link to increasing/decreasing activity in act_function_notation</todo>

            <p>Another characteristic we can describe with inequalities <term>concavity</term><index><main>concavity</main></index>. We say a function is <term>concave up</term> if its graph curves upward from left to right, and that it is <term>concave down</term> if it curves downward from left to right.</p>
            <example>
              <p>The efficiency graph has varying concavity depending on what section of inputs we use:<ul>
                  <li>
                      <p>concave down for <m>5\lt s\lt60</m>.</p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                      <p>concave up for <m>60\lt s\lt75</m>.</p>
                  </li>
                </ul></p>

